item.content:encoded:
Last week I started using the <a href="http://benalman.com/projects/jquery-postmessage-plugin/">Ben Alman jQuery plugin</a> for posting messages between different windows. Although it worked marvellously in modern browsers, Internet Explorer wouldn't work properly for some cases.

We're currently using postMessage/receiveMessage to dynamically resize an iframe inside our client's page. The plugin works in most browsers, including IE. But in my case, it was failing in IE when a form was submitted inside the iframe. It took us a long time to figure out the solution, but we finally came up with a fix.

In the plugin's website, they show and example of how to use it to communicate between two iframes residing in two different domains (<a href="http://benalman.com/code/projects/jquery-postmessage/examples/iframe/">http://benalman.com/code/projects/jquery-postmessage/examples/iframe/</a>). I'm going to use that example to show you how to solve it.

After a lot of debugging, we found out that the parent_url wasn't being set in IE after the form was submitted. So our solution was to add a hidden field that can hold the parent_url value when the iframe first loads.

Here's a quick example of how to fix the issue using the example posted in the plugins's website:

The child frame code

[js]
$(function(){
	var parent_url, link;

	// Create the hidden input field that will hold the parent_url variable.
	$(&quot;form&quot;).append('&lt;input id=&quot;parent_url&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; name=&quot;parent_url&quot; /&gt;');

	// We check to see if location hash is empty. It should only go in here if you're using IE and after the form as been submitted.
	if(document.location.hash == &quot;&quot;){
		var search 		= document.location.search,
				id 				= &quot;parent_url=&quot;,
				hs_start	= search.indexOf('parent_url'),
				hs_end 		= search.indexOf('&amp;product_service');

		// Get the parent URL from the URL parameters sent by the form
		parent_url = decodeURIComponent( search.substr(hs_start + id.length, hs_end - id.length - 1) );
	}
	// If location hash is not empty, then we just assign it to the variable parent_url
	else{
		parent_url = decodeURIComponent( document.location.hash.replace( /^#/, '' ) );
	}
	// We assign the value of the parent_url to the hidden input element. That way if document.location.hash is not accessible, it can be accessed
	$(&quot;#parent_url&quot;).val(parent_url);

	// This is the function that posts a message to the parent for it to resize the iframe
	function setHeight() {
		$.postMessage({ if_height: $('body').outerHeight( true ) }, parent_url, parent );
	};

	setHeight();
});
[/js]

The code for the parent window stays the same as in the example. After applying this changes, the code should work properly after submitting a form.

Also if you have links in your code and want your iframe to resize every time you go to a new page inside the iframe, try doing something like this in your iframe code:

[js]
// Go through each link and append the parent_url variable to the end.
$(&quot;a&quot;).each(function() {
	$(this).attr(&quot;href&quot;, $(this).attr(&quot;href&quot;)+&quot;#&quot;+parent_url);
});
[/js]

Hope this post saves somebody a bunch of hours of debugging and IE cursing. If you're having a similar problem implementing postMessage/receiveMessage, post a comment and we can figure out together.

